Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Caption", "Section",
 CellFrameColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108],
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108]],

Cell["\<\
With this Demonstration you can create interesting ribbon-like surfaces. The \
technique of superimposing two surfaces or connecting two curves to create a \
ribbon-type surface results in some very aesthetically pleasing and artistic \
designs not seen in any other Demonstration. The program is based on \
generalized three-dimensional Lissajous curves. Several additional options \
increase the freedom of artistic expression available.\
\>", "Text"]
}, Close]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Details", "Section",
 CellFrameColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108],
 FontColor->RGBColor[
  0.6449835965514611, 0.758632791638056, 0.2516823071641108]],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["General Controls",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
\"lighting\" setter bar: three types of lighting are provided. \
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
You can increase the plot range with the \"plot range\" slider (it can also \
be used to zoom).\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "You can choose to display a square \"floor\" showing the plot range in the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["x", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 "-",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["y", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " plane by checking \"floor\"."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Check/uncheck \"axes\" to display arrows for the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["x", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " axis (red), ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["y", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " axis (green), and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["z", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " axis (blue)."
}], "Text"],

Cell["\"background\" lets you select the background color.", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"curve number\"",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell["Here you choose which of two curves you want to edit. ", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
\"show both\": this lets you select whether you want to see the current \
surface only or the current surface as well as the stored second surface. \
(Remember that only the selected curve can be edited.)\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"store/restore/copy/reset\" setter bar",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
\"save\": stores the current settings to the storage of the selected curve.
\"restore\": restores the curve settings from storage.
\"copy\": copies the current settings to the storage area of both curves.
\"reset\": restores the currently edited curve to its default settings. \
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"surface\" checkbox",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "If the option \"surface\" is selected, the curve is connected to the origin \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"0", ",", "0", ",", "0"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " with many triangular polygons, and thus a warped surface is created (see \
also the description of \"width\" below)."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"lines\" checkbox",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The option \"lines\" only has an effect if \"surface\" has been selected.\n\
If the option \"lines\" is selected, each vertex is connected to the origin \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"0", ",", "0", ",", "0"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " by a black line. Also, a black rim runs along the curve. "
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"rim\" checkbox",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
If the option \"rim\" is selected, a black rim runs along the curve.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"colors\" selection",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
This defines the colors of the surface. A smooth color transition is used \
from the first color to the second and back to the first.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"width\" dropdown menu",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "If \"width\" is set to 1, then the surface (if selected) covers the area \
between the origin",
 " ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"0", ",", "0", ",", "0"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " ",
 "and the curve. "
}], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
If \"width\" is not 1, then the surface is the area between the curve and a \
second, similar, \"sister\" curve that is positioned between the original \
curve and the origin. Technically the sister curve is created by multiplying \
each vertex with the factor \"width\". \
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
Explore what happens when you set the width to very large or very small \
values!\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"effects\" checkboxes",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
First checkbox: if \"width\" is not 1, selecting this \"effect\" option \
creates an effect like sun rays. Instead of a ribbon, the area between the \
two sister curves is filled with a series of triangles.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
Second checkbox: when the surface is being created, only every second \
quadrilateral (or triangle, if the first checkbox is selected) is shown. Thus \
the surface created consists of a series of parallel stripes.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"opacity\" slider",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell["Defines the opacity of the surface.", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"frequencies\" dropdown menus",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The coordinate of the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["i", "th"], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " vertex of the currently edited object is calculated as "
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"x", "[", "i", "]"}], " ", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"sign", "(", "vx1", ")"}], "\[Times]", 
      RowBox[{"sin", "(", 
       RowBox[{"vx1", "\[Times]", "i", "\[Times]", "2", " ", 
        RowBox[{"\[Pi]", "/", "detail"}]}], ")"}]}], " ", "+", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"sign", "(", "vx2", ")"}], "\[Times]", 
      RowBox[{"cos", "(", 
       RowBox[{"vx2", "\[Times]", "i", "\[Times]", "2", " ", 
        RowBox[{"\[Pi]", "/", "detail"}]}], ")"}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineMath"],
 ","
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"y", "[", "i", "]"}], " ", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"sign", "(", "vy1", ")"}], "\[Times]", 
      RowBox[{"sin", "(", 
       RowBox[{"vy1", "\[Times]", "i", "\[Times]", "2", 
        RowBox[{"\[Pi]", "/", "detail"}]}], ")"}]}], " ", "+", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"sign", "(", "vy2", ")"}], "\[Times]", 
      RowBox[{"cos", "(", 
       RowBox[{"vy2", "\[Times]", "i", "\[Times]", "2", 
        RowBox[{"\[Pi]", "/", "detail"}]}], ")"}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineMath"],
 ","
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"z", "[", "i", "]"}], " ", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"sign", "(", "vz1", ")"}], "\[Times]", 
      RowBox[{"sin", "(", 
       RowBox[{"vz1", "\[Times]", "i", "\[Times]", "2", 
        RowBox[{"\[Pi]", "/", "detail"}]}], ")"}]}], " ", "+", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"sign", "(", "vz2", ")"}], "\[Times]", 
      RowBox[{"cos", "(", 
       RowBox[{"vz2", "\[Times]", "i", "\[Times]", "2", 
        RowBox[{"\[Pi]", "/", "detail"}]}], ")"}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]], 
  "InlineMath"],
 ","
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
   "vx1", ",", " ", "vx2", ",", " ", "vy1", ",", " ", "vy2", ",", " ", "vz1", 
    ",", " ", "vz2"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " are the \"frequencies\" selected from the dropdown menus, and \"detail\" \
is also selected from the associated dropdown menu."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The factors ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"sign", 
    RowBox[{"(", "vx1", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " and so on (which are either 1 or 0) have been introduced in order to \
enforce that the components with frequency 0 are ignored. So effectively we \
have "
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"sin", "[", 
     RowBox[{"frequency", " ", "0"}], "]"}], " ", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"cos", "[", 
      RowBox[{"frequency", " ", "0"}], "]"}], " ", "=", "0"}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 ". "
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The variable ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["i", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " counts the number of edges on the rim of the object. Hence it runs from 1 \
to the selected \"edges\" value. "
}], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
The higher the selected \"detail\", the smoother the curves and surfaces will \
be.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"rotate curve\" sliders",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell["These sliders control the rotation of the curve in space.", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "First (slider \"rot x\") the curve is rotated around the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["x", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " axis by the given value (in degrees),\nthen around the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["y", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " axis (slider \"rot y\"), and finally around the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["z", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath"],
 " axis (slider \"rot z\")."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["\"connect curves\" Controls",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
\"connect\" checkbox: this creates a ribbon-like surface between the two \
curves.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
\"lines\" checkbox: paints the boundary of small polygons (which make up the \
ribbon) black.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\"rim\" checkbox: paints boundary of ribbon black.", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
\"colors\": defines the colors of the ribbon. A smooth color transition is \
used from the first color to the second and back to the first.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
\"width\" dropdown menu: defines the width of this ribbon. The default value \
is 1, which means that the ribbon connects both curves. Smaller values create \
a more narrow ribbon. This more narrow ribbon still connects to the current \
curve, but does not connect to the other curve anymore. Explore what happens \
when you set the width to very large or very small values! \
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
\"effects\" checkboxes:
First checkbox: checking it connects the curves with a series of triangles.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
Second toggle: only every second quadrilateral (or triangle, if first \
checkbox is selected) is created. Thus the connection between the curves \
consists of a series of parallel stripes.\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["You cannot store or restore these \"connect curves\" controls.", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["Hints",
 FontSize->11,
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
If you selected integer values for all frequencies, you get closed surfaces \
by setting \"edges\" equal to \"details\".\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
If you selected a half-integer frequency, you get closed surfaces by setting \
\"edges\" to twice the value of \"details\".\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
If you selected frequencies as multiples of .1, then you get closed surfaces \
by setting \"edges\" to 10 times the value of \"details\".\
\>", "Text"],

Cell["\<\
Smooth color transitions need an associated single run through the \
parametrization of a closed curve. Therefore, if one curve uses integer \
frequencies, for nice color transitions it is best to select integer \
frequencies for the second curve as well; similar for half-integer \
frequencies, and so on.\
\>", "Text"]
}, Close]],

